<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
<meta charset="UTF-8">
<meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
<title>busco2aster Visual Report</title>
<style>
:root {
  --bg: #ffffff;
  --fg: #1a1a1a;
  --muted: #6b7280;
  --border: #e5e7eb;
  --accent: #2563eb;
  --success: #059669;
  --warning: #d97706;
  --danger: #dc2626;
  --surface: #f9fafb;
}
*, *::before, *::after { box-sizing: border-box; }
body {
  font-family: -apple-system, BlinkMacSystemFont, "Segoe UI", Roboto, "Helvetica Neue", Arial, sans-serif;
  color: var(--fg);
  background: var(--bg);
  margin: 0;
  padding: 0;
  line-height: 1.6;
}
.container { max-width: 1400px; margin: 0 auto; padding: 0 2rem; }
header {
  background: linear-gradient(135deg, #1e3a5f 0%, #2563eb 100%);
  color: white;
  padding: 2rem 0;
  margin-bottom: 2rem;
}
header h1 { margin: 0 0 0.25rem 0; font-size: 1.75rem; font-weight: 600; }
header p { margin: 0; opacity: 0.85; font-size: 0.95rem; }
nav#toc {
  position: sticky;
  top: 0;
  background: var(--bg);
  border-bottom: 1px solid var(--border);
  z-index: 100;
  padding: 0.5rem 0;
}
nav#toc .container {
  display: flex;
  flex-wrap: wrap;
  gap: 0.25rem 1.25rem;
}
nav#toc a {
  color: var(--accent);
  text-decoration: none;
  font-size: 0.85rem;
  white-space: nowrap;
}
nav#toc a:hover { text-decoration: underline; }
section { margin-bottom: 3rem; }
h2 {
  font-size: 1.4rem;
  font-weight: 600;
  border-bottom: 2px solid var(--accent);
  padding-bottom: 0.4rem;
  margin-top: 2rem;
}
h3 { font-size: 1.1rem; font-weight: 600; margin-top: 1.5rem; }
.caption {
  font-size: 0.88rem;
  color: var(--muted);
  margin-top: 0.5rem;
  margin-bottom: 1.5rem;
  line-height: 1.5;
}
.chart-container { width: 100%; margin-bottom: 0.5rem; }
.chart-row {
  display: grid;
  grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr;
  gap: 1.5rem;
  margin-bottom: 1rem;
}
@media (max-width: 900px) { .chart-row { grid-template-columns: 1fr; } }
.table-wrapper {
  overflow-x: auto;
  margin: 1rem 0;
  border: 1px solid var(--border);
  border-radius: 6px;
}
table {
  width: 100%;
  border-collapse: collapse;
  font-size: 0.88rem;
  min-width: 600px;
}
thead th {
  position: sticky;
  top: 0;
  background: var(--surface);
  border-bottom: 2px solid var(--border);
  padding: 0.6rem 0.75rem;
  text-align: left;
  font-weight: 600;
  white-space: nowrap;
}
tbody td {
  padding: 0.5rem 0.75rem;
  border-bottom: 1px solid var(--border);
}
tbody tr:hover { background: var(--surface); }
.summary-grid {
  display: grid;
  grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fit, minmax(200px, 1fr));
  gap: 1rem;
  margin: 1rem 0;
}
.summary-card {
  background: var(--surface);
  border: 1px solid var(--border);
  border-radius: 8px;
  padding: 1rem;
}
.summary-card .value {
  font-size: 1.5rem;
  font-weight: 700;
  color: var(--accent);
}
.summary-card .label {
  font-size: 0.82rem;
  color: var(--muted);
  margin-top: 0.2rem;
}
.info-box {
  background: #eff6ff;
  border-left: 4px solid var(--accent);
  padding: 1rem 1.25rem;
  margin: 1rem 0;
  border-radius: 0 6px 6px 0;
  font-size: 0.9rem;
}
.warn-box {
  background: #fffbeb;
  border-left: 4px solid var(--warning);
  padding: 1rem 1.25rem;
  margin: 1rem 0;
  border-radius: 0 6px 6px 0;
  font-size: 0.9rem;
}
details {
  margin: 1rem 0;
  border: 1px solid var(--border);
  border-radius: 6px;
}
details summary {
  padding: 0.75rem 1rem;
  cursor: pointer;
  font-weight: 600;
  background: var(--surface);
  border-radius: 6px;
}
details[open] summary { border-bottom: 1px solid var(--border); border-radius: 6px 6px 0 0; }
details .content { padding: 1rem; }
.toggle-btn {
  background: var(--accent);
  color: white;
  border: none;
  padding: 0.4rem 1rem;
  border-radius: 4px;
  cursor: pointer;
  font-size: 0.85rem;
  margin: 0.5rem 0.25rem 0.5rem 0;
}
.toggle-btn:hover { opacity: 0.9; }
.toggle-btn.active { background: #1d4ed8; }
#tree-container { width: 100%; min-height: 400px; border: 1px solid var(--border); border-radius: 6px; overflow: hidden; }
#tree-container svg { width: 100%; }
.pipeline-flow {
  display: flex;
  flex-wrap: wrap;
  align-items: center;
  gap: 0.5rem;
  margin: 1rem 0;
}
.pipeline-step {
  background: var(--surface);
  border: 1px solid var(--border);
  border-radius: 6px;
  padding: 0.5rem 1rem;
  font-size: 0.85rem;
  font-weight: 500;
}
.pipeline-arrow { color: var(--muted); font-size: 1.2rem; }
footer {
  border-top: 1px solid var(--border);
  padding: 1.5rem 0;
  margin-top: 3rem;
  font-size: 0.82rem;
  color: var(--muted);
}
dl.glossary dt { font-weight: 600; margin-top: 0.75rem; }
dl.glossary dd { margin-left: 1.5rem; margin-bottom: 0.5rem; }
@media print {
  nav#toc, .toggle-btn { display: none; }
  body { font-size: 10pt; }
  .chart-row { grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr; }
}
</style>
</head>
<body>

<header>
  <div class="container">
    <h1>busco2aster Visual Report</h1>
    <p>Phylogenomic analysis: {{ summary.sample_count }} taxa &middot; {{ summary.retained_loci }} loci &middot; {{ summary.sequence_type }} sequences</p>
  </div>
</header>

<nav id="toc">
  <div class="container">
    <a href="#summary">Summary</a>
    <a href="#pipeline">Pipeline</a>
    <a href="#dataset-qc">Dataset QC</a>
    <a href="#species-tree">Species Tree</a>
    <a href="#branch-support">Branch Support</a>
    <a href="#conflict">Conflict</a>
    <a href="#heterogeneity">Gene-tree Heterogeneity</a>
    {% if topo_tests_available %}<a href="#topology-tests">Topology Tests</a>{% endif %}
    <a href="#glossary">Glossary</a>
  </div>
</nav>

<main class="container">

<!-- ═══════════════════════ EXECUTIVE SUMMARY ═══════════════════════ -->
<section id="summary">
<h2>Executive Summary</h2>
<div class="summary-grid">
  <div class="summary-card">
    <div class="value">{{ summary.sample_count }}</div>
    <div class="label">Taxa analyzed</div>
  </div>
  <div class="summary-card">
    <div class="value">{{ summary.retained_loci }}</div>
    <div class="label">Retained loci (of {{ summary.candidate_loci }} candidates)</div>
  </div>
  <div class="summary-card">
    <div class="value">{{ summary.sequence_type }}</div>
    <div class="label">Sequence type</div>
  </div>
  <div class="summary-card">
    <div class="value">{{ "%.0f"|format(summary.mean_alignment_length_sites) }} {{ summary.sequence_length_unit }}</div>
    <div class="label">Mean alignment length</div>
  </div>
  <div class="summary-card">
    <div class="value">{{ summary.complete_taxon_gene_tree_count }}</div>
    <div class="label">Complete-taxon gene trees (of {{ summary.gene_tree_count }} total)</div>
  </div>
  <div class="summary-card">
    <div class="value">{{ "%.1f"|format(summary.mean_retained_missing_fraction * 100) }}%</div>
    <div class="label">Mean locus missingness</div>
  </div>
</div>
<p class="caption">
  <strong>Retained loci</strong> are BUSCO single-copy orthologs present in at least
  the occupancy threshold fraction of taxa. <strong>Complete-taxon gene trees</strong>
  contain all {{ summary.sample_count }} taxa, enabling direct topology comparisons.
  <strong>Missingness</strong> is the average fraction of retained loci absent per taxon.
</p>
</section>

<!-- ═══════════════════════ PIPELINE OVERVIEW ═══════════════════════ -->
<section id="pipeline">
<h2>Pipeline Overview</h2>
<div class="pipeline-flow">
  <div class="pipeline-step">Genome assemblies</div>
  <div class="pipeline-arrow">&rarr;</div>
  <div class="pipeline-step">BUSCO orthologs</div>
  <div class="pipeline-arrow">&rarr;</div>
  <div class="pipeline-step">MAFFT alignment</div>
  <div class="pipeline-arrow">&rarr;</div>
  <div class="pipeline-step">IQ-TREE gene trees</div>
  <div class="pipeline-arrow">&rarr;</div>
  <div class="pipeline-step">wASTRAL species tree</div>
  <div class="pipeline-arrow">&rarr;</div>
  <div class="pipeline-step">Concordance (gCF/sCF)</div>
  <div class="pipeline-arrow">&rarr;</div>
  <div class="pipeline-step">Report</div>
</div>
<p class="caption">
  The pipeline identifies shared single-copy orthologs via BUSCO, aligns them with MAFFT,
  infers per-locus gene trees with IQ-TREE 3, and summarizes them into a coalescent species
  tree using wASTRAL. Branch support is assessed via gene concordance factors (gCF),
  site concordance factors (sCF), and ASTER quartet posteriors.
</p>
</section>

<!-- ═══════════════════════ DATASET QC ═══════════════════════ -->
<section id="dataset-qc">
<h2>Dataset Quality Control</h2>

<h3>BUSCO Completeness</h3>
<div class="chart-container" id="chart-busco"></div>
<p class="caption">
  <strong>BUSCO completeness</strong> measures how many of the expected universal single-copy
  orthologs are found in each genome assembly. The x-axis shows the percentage of BUSCO genes
  in each category: <em>single-copy</em> (ideal &mdash; one copy found), <em>multi-copy</em>
  (duplicated), <em>fragmented</em> (partial match), and <em>missing</em> (not found).
  Assemblies with &gt;90% single-copy are considered high quality for phylogenomics.
</p>

<h3>Retained-locus Missingness</h3>
<div class="chart-container" id="chart-missingness"></div>
<p class="caption">
  For each taxon, this shows what fraction of the retained loci are <em>present</em> (the taxon
  contributed a sequence) versus <em>missing</em> (the locus was absent or excluded for that taxon).
  High missingness for a single taxon can reduce phylogenetic resolution and introduce bias.
</p>

<div class="chart-row">
  <div>
    <h3>Alignment Length Distribution</h3>
    <div class="chart-container" id="chart-alignment"></div>
    <p class="caption">
      Distribution of alignment lengths across all retained loci.
      The x-axis shows alignment length in {{ summary.sequence_length_unit }}
      ({{ "amino acids" if summary.sequence_type == "protein" else "nucleotides" }});
      the y-axis shows the number of loci. Very short alignments may lack
      phylogenetic signal; very long ones may contain non-orthologous regions.
    </p>
  </div>
  <div>
    <h3>Locus Filtering Outcomes</h3>
    <div class="chart-container" id="chart-filtering"></div>
    <p class="caption">
      Reasons why candidate loci were excluded from the analysis.
      <em>low_occupancy</em> means the locus was present in too few taxa (below the
      occupancy threshold). Other reasons may include sequence quality issues.
      {{ summary.retained_loci }} of {{ summary.candidate_loci }} candidate loci were retained.
    </p>
  </div>
</div>
</section>

<!-- ═══════════════════════ SPECIES TREE ═══════════════════════ -->
<section id="species-tree">
<h2>Species Tree</h2>
<p>
  The species tree was inferred by wASTRAL under the multispecies coalescent model.
  Internal branches are labeled <strong>B1, B2, ...</strong> &mdash; these labels are used
  as join keys in the concordance and conflict tables below. Tip labels show the full
  taxon names. Use the buttons to switch between cladogram (equal branch lengths, emphasizing
  topology) and phylogram (branch lengths proportional to coalescent units) views.
</p>
<div>
  <button class="toggle-btn active" id="btn-cladogram" onclick="setTreeLayout('cladogram')">Cladogram</button>
  <button class="toggle-btn" id="btn-phylogram" onclick="setTreeLayout('phylogram')">Phylogram</button>
</div>
<div id="tree-container"></div>
</section>

<!-- ═══════════════════════ BRANCH SUPPORT ═══════════════════════ -->
<section id="branch-support">
<h2>Branch Support &amp; Concordance</h2>

<div class="info-box">
  <strong>How to read this section:</strong> Each internal branch of the species tree is
  assessed by multiple independent support metrics. High values across all metrics indicate
  a well-resolved branch. Discordance between metrics can reveal incomplete lineage sorting
  (ILS), hybridization, or model violations. See the <a href="#glossary">Glossary</a> for
  detailed metric definitions.
</div>

<div class="chart-container" id="chart-branch-support"></div>
<p class="caption">
  Per-branch support metrics plotted side by side. The x-axis shows the score (0&ndash;100%
  or 0&ndash;100 for concordance factors). Each dot represents one metric for one branch.
  <strong>ASTER support</strong> is the local posterior probability from wASTRAL;
  <strong>ASTER q1</strong> is the quartet frequency supporting this topology;
  <strong>gCF</strong> is the fraction of decisive gene trees concordant with the branch;
  <strong>sCF</strong> is the fraction of decisive sites concordant. Branches where gCF &lt; 50%
  or sCF &lt; 50% may be unreliable.
</p>

<h3>Branch Metrics Table</h3>
<div class="table-wrapper">
<table id="table-branch-metrics">
  <thead>
    <tr>
      <th>Branch</th>
      <th>Split</th>
      <th>ASTER support (%)</th>
      <th>ASTER q1 (%)</th>
      <th>gCF</th>
      <th>sCF</th>
      <th>Branch length</th>
    </tr>
  </thead>
  <tbody>
    {% for b in branch_metrics %}
    <tr>
      <td><strong>{{ b.label }}</strong></td>
      <td style="font-size:0.82rem">{{ b.split_left | replace(",", ", ") }}<br><em>vs</em> {{ b.split_right | replace(",", ", ") }}</td>
      <td>{{ "%.1f"|format(b.aster_local_posterior * 100) }}</td>
      <td>{{ "%.1f"|format(b.aster_q1 * 100) }}</td>
      <td>{{ "%.1f"|format(b.gcf) }}</td>
      <td>{{ "%.1f"|format(b.scfl) }}</td>
      <td>{{ "%.4f"|format(b.species_tree_branch_length) }}</td>
    </tr>
    {% endfor %}
  </tbody>
</table>
</div>
<p class="caption">
  <strong>ASTER support</strong>: local posterior probability that the branch is correct under the
  multispecies coalescent (values &gt;0.95 are well supported).
  <strong>ASTER q1</strong>: fraction of input quartet trees that agree with this branch.
  <strong>gCF</strong>: gene concordance factor &mdash; percentage of decisive gene trees
  whose topology agrees with this branch (IQ-TREE).
  <strong>sCF</strong>: site concordance factor &mdash; percentage of decisive alignment sites
  supporting this branch (IQ-TREE).
  <strong>Branch length</strong>: in coalescent units (longer = more gene-tree agreement expected).
</p>
</section>

<!-- ═══════════════════════ CONFLICT ═══════════════════════ -->
<section id="conflict">
<h2>Conflict &amp; Alternative Resolutions</h2>

<p>
  Every internal branch has two possible alternative topologies (NNI neighbors).
  The charts below show how gene trees and sites are distributed across the main
  topology and its two alternatives. In a fully resolved tree, the main topology
  dominates; when alternatives have substantial support, the branch is genuinely
  ambiguous.
</p>

<h3>Gene Concordance Factor Breakdown</h3>
<div class="chart-container" id="chart-gcf-conflict"></div>
<p class="caption">
  For each branch, the stacked bar shows the fraction of decisive gene trees supporting
  the main topology (<strong>gCF</strong>), the first NNI alternative (<strong>gDF1</strong>),
  the second alternative (<strong>gDF2</strong>), and those uninformative for this branch
  (<strong>gDFP</strong>). Bars should sum to ~100%.
</p>

<h3>Site Concordance Factor Breakdown</h3>
<div class="chart-container" id="chart-scf-conflict"></div>
<p class="caption">
  Analogous to the gene-tree breakdown but at the site level. <strong>sCF</strong> is the
  fraction of decisive sites supporting the main topology; <strong>sDF1</strong> and
  <strong>sDF2</strong> support the two alternatives. Under ILS alone, the two alternative
  fractions should be approximately equal.
</p>

<h3>ASTER Quartet Alternatives</h3>
<div class="chart-container" id="chart-aster-conflict"></div>
<p class="caption">
  Quartet-based topology frequencies from wASTRAL. <strong>q1</strong> is the fraction of
  quartets supporting the main topology; <strong>q2</strong> and <strong>q3</strong> support
  the two NNI alternatives. Under pure ILS, q2 &approx; q3; substantial asymmetry may
  indicate hybridization or systematic error.
</p>
</section>

<!-- ═══════════════════════ GENE-TREE HETEROGENEITY ═══════════════════════ -->
<section id="heterogeneity">
<h2>Gene-tree Heterogeneity</h2>

<p>
  This section focuses on complete-taxon gene trees (those containing all {{ summary.sample_count }}
  taxa), because topology comparisons are only meaningful when the taxon set is identical.
</p>

<div class="chart-row">
  <div>
    <h3>RF Distance to Species Tree</h3>
    <div class="chart-container" id="chart-rf"></div>
    <p class="caption">
      The Robinson-Foulds (RF) distance counts the number of bipartitions that differ
      between each gene tree and the species tree. An RF distance of 0 means the gene tree
      has the same topology as the species tree. Higher values indicate greater discordance,
      which may be caused by incomplete lineage sorting, horizontal gene transfer, or
      phylogenetic estimation error.
    </p>
  </div>
  <div>
    <h3>Top Gene-tree Topologies</h3>
    <div class="chart-container" id="chart-topologies"></div>
    <p class="caption">
      The most frequent gene-tree topologies among complete-taxon trees. Green bars match
      the species tree topology; red bars represent alternative topologies. The species tree
      topology is expected to be the most common, but under strong ILS many loci may show
      alternative arrangements.
    </p>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="chart-row">
  <div>
    <h3>Substitution Models</h3>
    <div class="chart-container" id="chart-models"></div>
    <p class="caption">
      The most frequently selected substitution models across all gene trees, chosen by
      IQ-TREE's ModelFinder. This reveals the typical sequence evolution patterns in the dataset.
      {% if summary.sequence_type == "protein" %}
      Common protein models include LG, WAG, and JTT, with rate heterogeneity modeled
      by +G (gamma) or +I+G (invariant sites + gamma).
      {% else %}
      Common DNA models include GTR, HKY, and TN, with rate heterogeneity modeled
      by +G (gamma) or +I+G (invariant sites + gamma).
      {% endif %}
    </p>
  </div>
  <div>
    <h3>Branch Support Coverage</h3>
    <div class="chart-container" id="chart-support-coverage"></div>
    <p class="caption">
      How many gene trees have branch support values (aBayes posteriors or ultrafast bootstrap).
      Trees without support values may indicate alignment issues or very short sequences where
      the support method could not be computed.
    </p>
  </div>
</div>
</section>

<!-- ═══════════════════════ TOPOLOGY TESTS ═══════════════════════ -->
{% if topo_tests_available %}
<section id="topology-tests">
<h2>Topological Uncertainty</h2>

<p>
  This section evaluates whether the inferred species tree topology is statistically
  distinguishable from alternative topologies. Two complementary approaches are used:
  <strong>quartet posteriors</strong> (coalescent-based, from wASTRAL) and the
  <strong>AU test</strong> (concatenation-based, from IQ-TREE).
</p>

<h3>Quartet Posterior Probabilities</h3>
<div class="table-wrapper">
<table>
  <thead>
    <tr>
      <th>Branch</th>
      <th>pp1</th>
      <th>pp2</th>
      <th>pp3</th>
      <th>q1</th>
      <th>q2</th>
      <th>q3</th>
      <th>Contested</th>
    </tr>
  </thead>
  <tbody>
    {% for b in branch_quartet_support %}
    <tr>
      <td><strong>{{ b.branch_id }}</strong></td>
      <td>{{ "%.4f"|format(b.pp1) }}</td>
      <td>{{ "%.4f"|format(b.pp2) }}</td>
      <td>{{ "%.4f"|format(b.pp3) }}</td>
      <td>{{ "%.4f"|format(b.q1) }}</td>
      <td>{{ "%.4f"|format(b.q2) }}</td>
      <td>{{ "%.4f"|format(b.q3) }}</td>
      <td>{{ "Yes" if b.contested else "" }}</td>
    </tr>
    {% endfor %}
  </tbody>
</table>
</div>
<p class="caption">
  <strong>pp1, pp2, pp3</strong>: posterior probabilities for the main topology and its two NNI
  alternatives, estimated under the multispecies coalescent. A branch is flagged as
  <strong>contested</strong> when pp1 falls below the configured threshold (default 0.95),
  indicating the data do not strongly favor one topology.
  <strong>q1, q2, q3</strong>: the corresponding quartet frequency proportions.
</p>

<h3>AU Topology Test Results</h3>
<div class="table-wrapper">
<table>
  <thead>
    <tr>
      <th>Tree</th>
      <th>Description</th>
      <th>Source</th>
      <th>logL</th>
      <th>&Delta;L</th>
      <th>p-AU</th>
      <th>In confidence set</th>
    </tr>
  </thead>
  <tbody>
    {% for r in au_test_results %}
    <tr>
      <td>{{ r.tree_index }}</td>
      <td>{{ r.description }}</td>
      <td>{{ r.source }}</td>
      <td>{{ "%.2f"|format(r.logL) if r.logL is not none else "" }}</td>
      <td>{{ "%.2f"|format(r.deltaL) if r.deltaL is not none else "" }}</td>
      <td>{{ "%.4f"|format(r.p_au) if r.p_au is not none else "n/a" }}</td>
      <td>{{ "Yes" if r.in_confidence_set else "No" }}</td>
    </tr>
    {% endfor %}
  </tbody>
</table>
</div>
<p class="caption">
  The approximately unbiased (AU) test evaluates candidate tree topologies against a
  concatenated supermatrix. <strong>logL</strong> is the log-likelihood; <strong>&Delta;L</strong>
  is the difference from the best tree. <strong>p-AU</strong> &ge; 0.05 means the topology cannot
  be rejected at the 5% level and belongs to the <strong>95% confidence set</strong>.
</p>

<div class="info-box">
  <strong>Interpretation guide</strong>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Agreement:</strong> When a contested branch (low pp1) also has an alternative tree
      in the AU confidence set, both coalescent and concatenation perspectives agree that the
      branch is genuinely unresolved &mdash; the strongest signal of topological ambiguity.</li>
    <li><strong>Low pp1, AU rejects alternative:</strong> May indicate systematic error
      (e.g., long-branch attraction) rather than ILS.</li>
    <li><strong>High pp1, AU keeps alternative:</strong> May indicate ILS that concatenation
      cannot model &mdash; the coalescent-aware method has higher power for ILS detection.</li>
  </ul>
</div>
</section>
{% endif %}

<!-- ═══════════════════════ GLOSSARY ═══════════════════════ -->
<section id="glossary">
<h2>Glossary &amp; Methods</h2>

<details open>
<summary>Metric Definitions</summary>
<div class="content">
<dl class="glossary">
  <dt>BUSCO</dt>
  <dd>Benchmarking Universal Single-Copy Orthologs. A standardized set of genes expected to
    be present in single copy across a clade. Used here to identify orthologous loci for
    phylogenomic analysis.</dd>

  <dt>Occupancy</dt>
  <dd>The fraction of taxa in which a given locus is present. Loci below the occupancy
    threshold (default 0.8) are excluded to avoid missing-data artifacts.</dd>

  <dt>gCF (Gene Concordance Factor)</dt>
  <dd>The percentage of decisive gene trees whose topology agrees with a given branch of the
    species tree. Computed by IQ-TREE. Values near 100% indicate strong gene-tree support;
    values below 50% suggest the branch may be incorrect or affected by strong ILS.</dd>

  <dt>gDF1, gDF2 (Gene Discordance Factors)</dt>
  <dd>The percentage of decisive gene trees supporting the first and second NNI alternative
    topologies at a branch. gCF + gDF1 + gDF2 + gDFP &approx; 100%.</dd>

  <dt>gDFP (Gene Discordance Factor, Polytomy)</dt>
  <dd>The percentage of decisive gene trees that are uninformative for a branch (i.e., the
    branch is a polytomy in the gene tree).</dd>

  <dt>sCF (Site Concordance Factor)</dt>
  <dd>The percentage of decisive alignment sites supporting a branch. Analogous to gCF but
    at the individual-site level. Computed by IQ-TREE using quartet sampling.</dd>

  <dt>sDF1, sDF2 (Site Discordance Factors)</dt>
  <dd>Site-level support for the two NNI alternative topologies. Under ILS alone,
    sDF1 &approx; sDF2.</dd>

  <dt>ASTER Local Posterior (pp)</dt>
  <dd>The posterior probability that a branch is correct under the multispecies coalescent
    model, computed by wASTRAL. Values &gt;0.95 indicate strong support.</dd>

  <dt>Quartet Frequencies (q1, q2, q3)</dt>
  <dd>The proportions of input quartet trees supporting the main topology (q1) and its two
    NNI alternatives (q2, q3). These sum to 1.0 and quantify how much of the quartet
    signal favors each resolution.</dd>

  <dt>pp1, pp2, pp3</dt>
  <dd>Posterior probabilities for the three possible resolutions at each branch, computed by
    wASTRAL with -u 2. pp1 corresponds to the main topology; pp2 and pp3 to the two NNI
    alternatives. pp1 + pp2 + pp3 = 1.0.</dd>

  <dt>RF Distance (Robinson-Foulds)</dt>
  <dd>The number of bipartitions that differ between two unrooted trees. A standard metric
    of topological dissimilarity. RF = 0 means the trees have identical topologies.</dd>

  <dt>AU Test (Approximately Unbiased)</dt>
  <dd>A statistical test that evaluates whether candidate tree topologies can be distinguished
    based on a concatenated sequence alignment. Trees with p-AU &ge; 0.05 cannot be rejected
    and belong to the 95% confidence set.</dd>

  <dt>ILS (Incomplete Lineage Sorting)</dt>
  <dd>A biological process where ancestral polymorphisms persist through speciation events,
    causing gene trees to differ from the species tree. ILS is the primary source of
    gene-tree discordance in closely related species.</dd>

  <dt>Coalescent Unit</dt>
  <dd>The unit of branch length in a species tree estimated under the multispecies coalescent.
    Longer branches (in coalescent units) have less expected discordance from ILS.</dd>

  <dt>NNI (Nearest-Neighbor Interchange)</dt>
  <dd>A tree rearrangement operation that swaps two subtrees across an internal branch,
    producing the two possible alternative topologies for that branch.</dd>
</dl>
</div>
</details>

<details>
